  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison tells about his reply to Wendell Phillips&apos;s accusations against him in the legal case concerning Francis Jackson&apos;s bequest. In response to Alfred H. Love&apos;s criticism that certain lines in William Lloyd Garrison&apos;s reply are not &quot;Garrison-like,&quot; Garrison says that he has never been &quot;given to circumlocution, and never hesitates to &apos;call a spade a spade.&apos;&quot; Garrison defends his reply to Wendell Phillips&apos;s criticism and his actions in connection with the Jackson bequest. Wendell Phillips refuses to pay the money over to the New England Freedmen&apos;s Aid Commission.</subfield>
